	"nodes":[
		{"id":"c47c1388e0c519e7","type":"group","x":-1400,"y":-700,"width":340,"height":260,"color":"6","label":"Set Cursor"},
		{"id":"8789741aeabc122b","type":"group","x":-1400,"y":-380,"width":290,"height":160,"color":"1","label":"QID Seed"},
		{"id":"7a3571afff2bf06a","type":"text","text":"Set cursor rules.","x":-1380,"y":-680,"width":160,"height":50,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"35256e21cc6d3efa","type":"text","text":"Create QIDs\n## QID autopopulation: when, how, and whether you need a table\n\n### What QID _is_ in your laws\n\n- **Global, immutable, opaque ID** for a node.\n    \n- Not derived from filename, not derived from QiDecimal.\n    \n- Never changes once assigned.\n    \n    0.00.01.15_qid\n    \n\n### Do you need a table?\n\n**Yes.**  \nYou need a **single source of truth** for the next QID, otherwise:\n\n- two workers race,\n    \n- you get collisions,\n    \n- your “lifetime brain” starts hallucinating duplicates.\n    \n\n### Minimal canon design\n\nAdd this table:\n\n`create table if not exists public.qid_counter (   id boolean primary key default true,   next_qid bigint not null,   updated_at timestamptz default now() );  insert into public.qid_counter (id, next_qid) values (true, 1) on conflict (id) do nothing;`\n\nThen a function to atomically claim one:\n\n`create or replace function public.claim_qid() returns bigint language plpgsql as $$ declare   claimed bigint; begin   update public.qid_counter   set next_qid = next_qid + 1,       updated_at = now()   where id = true   returning next_qid - 1 into claimed;    return claimed; end; $$;`\n\n### When does it run?\n\n**Layer 5 — Metadata.**\n\nWorker logic:\n\n- If a file/node has no `qid` in front matter:\n    \n    - call `claim_qid()`\n        \n    - write it into YAML + DB row\n        \n- If it already has one:\n    \n    - never touch it.\n        \n\nThat’s autopopulation. Clean and lawful.","x":-1380,"y":-360,"width":250,"height":50,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"f983a247140370c7","type":"text","text":"QiOS QID Counter Seed\n\n-- Minimal canon design for atomic QID generation\n\n-- Run once in `qios-core`:\n\n  \n\n-- QID Counter Table\n\n-- Single-row table with boolean primary key (always true)\n\n-- Stores the next QID to be claimed in a global monotonic sequence\n\ncreate table if not exists public.qid_counter (\n\n  id boolean primary key default true,\n\n  next_qid bigint not null,\n\n  updated_at timestamptz default now()\n\n);\n\n  \n\n-- Initialize counter to 1 (first QID will be 1)\n\ninsert into public.qid_counter (id, next_qid)\n\nvalues (true, 1)\n\non conflict (id) do nothing;\n\n  \n\n-- Atomic QID Claim Function\n\n-- Atomically increments counter and returns the claimed QID\n\n-- Thread-safe: uses UPDATE with RETURNING to prevent race conditions\n\ncreate or replace function public.claim_qid()\n\nreturns bigint\n\nlanguage plpgsql\n\nas $$\n\ndeclare\n\n  claimed bigint;\n\nbegin\n\n  update public.qid_counter\n\n  set next_qid = next_qid + 1,\n\n      updated_at = now()\n\n  where id = true\n\n  returning next_qid - 1 into claimed;\n\n  \n\n  return claimed;\n\nend;\n\n$$;","x":-1380,"y":-300,"width":250,"height":50,"color":"1"},
